description: From Middle English frenetik (also frentik, frentyk, frantike > modern English frantic), from Old French frenetike, from Latin phreneticus, from Ancient Greek φρενητικός (phrenētikós, “delirious”), from φρενῖτις (phrenîtis, “delirium”), from φρήν (phrḗn, “mind”). Doublet of frantic.

adjectives.description: frenetic (comparative more frenetic, superlative most frenetic)

entries.meaning: Fast, harried; having extreme enthusiasm or energy.
examples: After a week of working at a frenetic pace, she was ready for Saturday.

entries.meaning: (obsolete, medicine) Characterised by manifestations of delirium or madness.
